Task: Given a number line from 0 to N, where N is a positive integer less than or equal to 10^6, and a probability P, find the probability that a person starting at position 0 will reach position N by making jumps of either 2 or 3 steps with probabilities P/100 and (100-P)/100, respectively.

Input: The input consists of a single line containing two integers N and P, where N is the final position on the number line and P is the probability of making a jump of 2 steps. The input is provided through standard input.

Output: The output should be a single floating-point number with exactly 6 digits after the decimal point, representing the probability of reaching the final position N. The output should be printed to standard output.

Constraints: The input integers N and P must satisfy the constraints 0 < N ≤ 10^6 and 0 ≤ P ≤ 100.

Task: Given an array A of N integers a1, a2, a3, ... aN, find the length of the longest alternating sub-sequence of A. An alternating sequence B of length K is a sequence that satisfies the following two conditions:
1. |b1|<|b2|<|b3|<.....<|bk|
2. The signs alternate between adjacent elements, i.e, if b1 > 0 then b2<0, b3 >0 and so on. Alternatively, if b1<0, then b2>0, b3<0 and so on.

Input: The input consists of two lines. The first line contains a single integer N, denoting the size of the array. The second line contains N integers a1, a2, a3, ... aN, denoting the array A.

Output: The output should be a single integer representing the length of the longest alternating sub-sequence of A.

Constraints: 1 ≤ N ≤ 5000, |ai| ≤ 10^9, ai not equal to 0. A sub-sequence of array A is a sequence obtained by dropping some elements of the array A.

Task: Given an array A of size N, convert it into a special array where all negative values appear at the beginning and all positive values form the tail of the array. Find the minimum number of values that should be changed in the given array to make it a special array. The special array must contain at least one negative and at least one positive value, and should not contain 0 as any of its value.

Input: The input consists of T test cases. For each test case, the first line contains an integer N denoting the size of the array, followed by N space-separated integers representing the elements of the array. The input is provided through standard input.

Output: For each test case, output a single integer representing the minimum number of values that should be changed in the given array to make it a special array. The output is printed to standard output.

Constraints: 1 ≤ T ≤ 10, 2 ≤ N ≤ 10^5, and 1 ≤ |Ai| ≤ 10^9, where || denotes the absolute value. The problem can be modeled as sorting the array such that all negative values appear before the positive values. The task is to find the minimum number of elements that need to be moved to achieve this sorting. The array must contain at least one negative and at least one positive value, and should not contain 0 as any of its value.

Task: Given an undirected acyclic graph (tree) with N nodes, where each node has an associated entrance fee represented by an integer Ci, find the maximum cost path between two given nodes X and Y. The cost of a path is the sum of entrance fees of all nodes on the path.

Input: The input consists of T test cases. Each test case starts with an integer N, the number of nodes in the tree, followed by N space-separated integers representing the entrance fees of each node. The next N-1 lines contain two space-separated integers X and Y, indicating that there is a bidirectional edge between nodes X and Y. Input is provided through standard input.

Output: For each test case, output the maximum cost path between the two given nodes in a new line. 

Constraints: 1 ≤ T ≤ 5, 1 ≤ N ≤ 50000, and -100000000 ≤ Ci ≤ 100000000, where Ci is the entrance fee of the ith node.

Task: Given a grid of size N x N, where each cell is either 0 or 1, find the number of paths from the top-left cell (1,1) to the bottom-right cell (N,N) such that the path only consists of cells with 0 and does not visit any cell more than once.

Input: The first line of input contains an integer N ( N ≤ 100), which is the size of the grid. The following N lines each contain N space-separated integers, representing the grid. The integers are either 0 or 1. The input is provided through standard input.

Output: A single line showing the number of paths from (1,1) to (N,N) that only consist of cells with 0 and do not visit any cell more than once.

Constraints: The size of the grid is at most 100, and each cell in the grid is represented by either 0 or 1.

Task: Given a sequence of integers, convert it into a strictly increasing sequence of positive integers, i.e., a beautiful sequence. You can change any element in the sequence, but you should make as few changes as possible to make it beautiful. For each test case, output the minimal number of elements that need to be changed to make the sequence beautiful.

Input: The input consists of T test cases. Each test case starts with an integer N (0 < N ≤ 100000), which is the number of elements in the original sequence. The second line contains N positive integers, no larger than 2000000000, which form the original sequence. Input is provided through standard input.

Output: For each test case, output a single integer which is the minimal number of elements that need to be changed in the original sequence to make it a beautiful sequence.

Constraints: The input sequence can have at most 100000 elements, and each element is a positive integer no larger than 2000000000. The number of test cases is at most 5.
